-- Balda, BASF, BMW, ThyssenKrupp May Move in Frankfurt: German Stock Preview
-- Julie Cruz
-- 2010-06-23T06:47:30Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-23/balda-basf-bmw-thyssenkrupp-may-move-in-frankfurt-german-stock-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in Germany. Stock
symbols are in parentheses and prices are from the last close.  
 DAX Index  futures expiring in September slid 0.7 percent to
6,229 as of 8:46 a.m. in Frankfurt. The benchmark DAX Index
dropped 0.4 percent to 6,269.04 yesterday.  
 Balda AG  (BAF GY): The German maker of mobile-phone casings
said it settled a lawsuit filed against a former consultant
“because of negligent advice.” The terms of the out-of-court
settlement were not stated in a company statement. The shares
gained 3 percent to 2.77 euros.  
 BASF SE  (BAS GY): The world’s largest chemicals company,
agreed to buy German food- and cosmetics-ingredients maker
Cognis Holding GmbH for an enterprise value of 3.1 billion euros
($3.8 billion) to accelerate its move away from commodity
chemicals. The shares dropped 0.3 percent to 46.74 euros.  
 Bayerische Motoren Werke AG  (BMW GY): The world’s largest
luxury-car manufacturer said there is a “dispute” between
workers and management at its dealership in Dalian, China,
following strikes at parts suppliers for Toyota Motor Corp. and
Honda Motor Co. The shares fell 0.7 percent to 41.52 euros.  
 ThyssenKrupp AG  (TKA GY): The steelmaker’s workers council
may block the company’s plan to sell metalworking operations,
Rheinische Post reported, citing group works council chairman
 Thomas Schlenz . The shares lost 0.9 percent to 22.40 euros.  
